dataNote: In 2020, our mobile forms were re-designed to capture wireless services in three distinct categories; 1. Mobile phone (handheld devices used mainly for voice and data communications, such as smartphones), 2. Mobile broadband (revenues and subscribers is defined as tablets, Internet access via netbooks and laptops; exclude mobile handheld devices such as blackberries, iphone, smartphones, etc.) and 3. Other plans for mobile connected devices (should include the number of plans for all other connected peripherials and devices, M2M services that are not included in or part of the mobile phones and mobile broadband categories).  Only <<Mobile phone>> subscribers were included in this survey. With respect to business subscriptions/accounts that may have multiple unique plans and many connected devices, please report the total number of plan.

dataNote: In Fiji, many people use multiple SIM cards and often subscribe to two different mobile operators. This is mainly due to differences in service quality especially internet speed which can vary by location. As a result, users tend to switch between operators depending on which one performs better in a particular area. Additionally, some individuals carry two mobile phones for convenience and better connectivity.

dataNote: Corresponds to mobile lines in service. Mobile lines in total suspension or cut off are excluded -which cannot receive or make phone calls-, as well as those that are in permanent cancellation. Lines are considered for the cellular mobile telephony service and for the closed user service (trunking).The reduction in the number of mobile telephone lines, according to information provided by operators, is mainly attributed to the cancellation of those lines that remained inactive for a period of more than three months. However, these lines are still above the total population.
seriesDescription: Refers to the number of subscriptions to a public mobile-telephone service that provide access to the public switched telephone network (PSTN) using cellular technology. It includes the number of postpaid subscriptions and the number of active prepaid accounts

dataNote: Corresponde a líneas móviles en servicio. Se excluyen las líneas móviles totalmente suspendidas o interrumpidas, que no pueden recibir ni realizar llamadas, así como las que se encuentran en cancelación permanente. Se consideran líneas para el servicio de telefonía móvil celular y para el servicio de usuario cerrado (trunking). La reducción en el número de líneas de telefonía móvil, según la información proporcionada por los operadores, se atribuye principalmente a la cancelación de las líneas que permanecieron inactivas durante más de tres meses. Sin embargo, estas líneas aún superan la población total.

dataNote: Data confirmed.The loss of customers was reported, in particular, by OPMS. This sharp decline was observed mainly in the first quarter of 2023 and is due to a combination of factors: 1. The restriction, in 2020, of the "Ugly" bundled tariff to young people up to the age of 23 (Regulator's decision) and its subsequent discontinuation in 2022 (operator's decision), which would have gradually led to a decrease in the duplication of OPMS SIM cards in its customer base, consequently reducing the number of active subscribers. 2. A significant emigration of the young population has occurred over the past two years. 3. OPMS's incorrect recording of the number of active subscribers, a fact that was only corrected with the change to its NGIN platform in early 2023, which automatically corrected the recording of active cards.

dataNote: The year saw sustained activity by operators pitching targeted value propositions following the COVID 19 pandemic lockdown in March 2020. Central to these value propositions are Work-From-Home packages as well as streaming services. Some of these players intimated that streaming traffic now accounts for more than 65% of their broadband traffic. In addition, the year witnessed the adoption of mobile money services. As COVID-19 was still very much in the public domain, it hastened the adoption of online and remote working methods. Many retailers and merchants shifted to digital payments over cash due to the reduced risk of exposure.
